    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! A confidentiality period in a contract is a time frame during which the parties involved must keep certain information secret. It's like a temporary agreement between you and the other party to not share the information with anyone else. On the other hand, a survival clause is a provision that ensures certain terms of the contract, like confidentiality, continue to apply even after the contract has ended. It's like a lingering presence of the contract's rules, even after the main agreement has been concluded. So, while the confidentiality period is a temporary restriction, the survival clause keeps the confidentiality requirement active even after the contract's life span.",
      "source": "target",
